The '''Center for World Indigenous Studies''' ('''CWIS''') is a non-profit [[United States|American]] organization. Founded in 1979 as a research and documentation clearing house, it was incorporated in 1984 by Rudolph C. Ryser, Ph.D. (who grew up as member of the [[Cowlitz (tribe)|Cowlitz tribe]] but was of [[Weskarini Algonquin First Nation|Weskarini]], [[Oneida people|Oneida]] and [[Cree]] heritage), and Chief [[George Manuel]] (1929–1989) of the [[Shuswaps|Shuswap nation]].
[[Joe DeLaCruz]] (1937–2000),<ref>{{cite web | url = http://nwindian.evergreen.edu/jdlc.html | title = The Joe DelaCruz Center for Advanced Studies in Tribal Government | publisher = Northwest Indian Applied Research Institute, [[The Evergreen State College]]}}</ref> a former president of the [[National Congress of American Indians]], was chair of public policy at CWIS.
